{
  "doc_id": "16726",
  "text": "Therefore, under the specific tested conditions, stallions can be kept in groups, because agonistic interactions are maintained at a minimum rate after the first few days following group integration, which corresponds to the rate observed among wild bachelor groups (1.4 interactions per hour in our study versus 1.5 in natural populations of Przewalski's horse, Equus ferus przewalskii [CITATION_1] ). We therefore encourage horse breeders with extensive pasture land to keep stallions in stable groups and in adequate densities [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , particularly for those that are not used for breeding the whole year around. This could potentially improve horse welfare and reduce labour associated with horse management (H. Besier and I. Bachmann, unpublished data).",
